message.content:
Cornus sanguinea is a deciduous shrub also known as European dogwood.
It grows to a height of up to 6 feet and a spread of 8 to 10 feet.
The bark is grey-brown and develops distinctive ridges and furrows with age.
The leaves are oval shaped, opposite and have a dark green color turning red in autumn.
The small white flowers bloom in June and July, followed by black berries in autumn.
Cornus sanguinea is used as an ornamental plant in gardens and parks.
It is also grown for it's wood, which is used in crafts and as firewood.
